/wiki/Aberavon_(UK_Parliament_constituen: Aberavon (Welsh: Aberafan) is a constituency represented in the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
/wiki/Ramsay_MacDonald: James Ramsay MacDonald FRS (né James McDonald Ramsay; 12 October 1866 – 9 November 1937) was a British statesman who was the first Labour Party politician to become Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, leading minority Labour governments for nine months in 1924 and then in 1929–31. From 1931 to 1935, he headed a National Government dominated by the Conservative Party and supported by only a few Labour members. MacDonald was later vehemently denounced by and expelled from the party he had helped to found.
/wiki/Accrington_(UK_Parliament_constitu: Accrington was a parliamentary constituency of the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom from 1885 to 1983. It elected one Member of Parliament (MP) by the first-past-the-post system of election.
/wiki/Charles_Roden_Buxton: Charles Roden Buxton (27 November 1875 – 16 December 1942) was an English philanthropist and radical British Liberal Party politician who later joined the Labour Party. He survived an assassination attempt during a mission to the Balkans in 1914.
/wiki/Bermondsey_West_(UK_Parliament_con: Bermondsey West was a parliamentary constituency centred on the Bermondsey district of South London.  It returned one Member of Parliament to the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
/wiki/Alfred_Salter: Alfred Salter (16 June 1873 – 24 August 1945) was a British medical practitioner and Labour Party politician.
/wiki/Birmingham_Ladywood_(UK_Parliament: Birmingham, Ladywood is a constituency[n 1] of part of the city of Birmingham, represented in the House of Commons.[n 2]
/wiki/Robert_Dunstan: Robert Dunstan (1877 – 1963) was a British doctor and political activist.
/wiki/Bishop_Auckland_(UK_Parliament_con: Bishop Auckland is a constituency[n 1] represented in the House of Commons of the UK Parliament since 2019 by Dehenna Davison, a Conservative.[n 2]
/wiki/Ben_Spoor: Benjamin Charles Spoor PC (2 June 1878 – 22 December 1928) was a British Labour Party politician. He took a particular interest in India.
/wiki/Blackburn_(UK_Parliament_constitue: Blackburn is a constituency[n 1] represented in the House of Commons of the UK Parliament.[n 2]
/wiki/John_Davies,_1st_Baron_Darwen: John Percival Davies, 1st Baron Darwen (28 March 1885 – 26 December 1950), was a British cotton manufacturer and Labour politician.
/wiki/Bradford_Central_(UK_Parliament_co: Bradford Central was a parliamentary constituency in the city of Bradford, West Yorkshire, which returned one Member of Parliament (MP) to the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom. Elections were held under the first-past-the-post voting system.
/wiki/William_Leach_(Labour_politician): William Leach (1870 – 21 November 1949) was a British Labour Party politician.
/wiki/Bradford_East_(UK_Parliament_const: Bradford East is a constituency[n 1] represented in the House of Commons of the UK Parliament. [n 2]
/wiki/Fred_Jowett: Frederick William Jowett (31 January 1864 – 1 February 1944) was a British Labour politician.
/wiki/Brigg_(UK_Parliament_constituency): Brigg was a county constituency centred on the town of Brigg in North Lincolnshire.  It returned one Member of Parliament (MP) to the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom, elected by the first-past-the-post voting system.
/wiki/David_Quibell: David John Kinsley Quibell, 1st Baron Quibell (21 December 1879 – 16 April 1962) was a British builder, contractor and Labour Party politician.
/wiki/Bristol_North_(UK_Parliament_const: Bristol North was a borough constituency which returned one Member of Parliament (MP) to the House of Commons of the UK Parliament from 1885 until it was abolished for the 1950 general election.
/wiki/Walter_Ayles: Walter Henry Ayles (24 March 1879 – 6 July 1953) was a British Labour Party politician who served as a Member of Parliament (MP) for 11 years between 1923 and 1953.
/wiki/Bute_and_North_Ayrshire_(UK_Parlia: Bute and Northern Ayrshire  was a county constituency of the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom from 1918 to 1983. It elected one Member of Parliament (MP) by the first past the post voting system.
/wiki/John_Paton_(British_politician): John Paton (8 August 1886 – 14 December 1976) was a Labour Party politician in the United Kingdom, and a Member of Parliament (MP) from 1945 to 1964.
/wiki/Caerphilly_(UK_Parliament_constitu: Caerphilly (Welsh: Caerffili) is a county constituency centred on the town of Caerphilly in South Wales.  It returns one Member of Parliament (MP) to the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom, elected by the first past the post voting system.
/wiki/Morgan_Jones_(Welsh_politician): Morgan Jones (3 May 1885 – 23 April 1939) was a Welsh Labour Party politician.
/wiki/Cardiff_Central_(UK_Parliament_con: Cardiff Central (Welsh: Canol Caerdydd) is a borough constituency in the city of Cardiff. It returns one Member of Parliament (MP) to the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom, elected by the first past the post system.
/wiki/James_Ewart_Edmunds: James Ewart Edmunds (5 May 1882 – 1962) was a Welsh trade unionist and politician.
/wiki/Chelsea_(UK_Parliament_constituenc: Chelsea was a borough constituency, represented in the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.
/wiki/Bertrand_Russell: Bertrand Arthur William Russell, 3rd Earl Russell, OM FRS (18 May 1872 – 2 February 1970) was a British philosopher, logician, mathematician, historian, writer, essayist, social critic, political activist, and Nobel laureate. At various points in his life, Russell considered himself a liberal, a socialist and a pacifist, although he also confessed that his sceptical nature had led him to feel that he had "never been any of these things, in any profound sense." Russell was born in Monmouthshire into one of the most prominent aristocratic families in the United Kingdom.
/wiki/Clackmannan_and_Eastern_Stirlingsh: Clackmannan and Eastern Stirlingshire was a parliamentary constituency in the Clackmannan area of Central Scotland. It returned one Member of Parliament (MP) to the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom, elected by the first past the post system.
/wiki/Lauchlin_MacNeill_Weir: Lauchlan MacNeill Weir (1877–18 August 1939) was a Scottish Labour politician.
/wiki/Colne_Valley_(UK_Parliament_consti: Colne Valley is a constituency[n 1] represented in the House of Commons of the UK Parliament since 2019 by Jason McCartney of the Conservative Party.[n 2]  The seat has been won by three different parties' candidates by a marginal majority since the 1992 general election, the last occasion when the winning majority exceeded 10% of the votes cast.
/wiki/Philip_Snowden: Philip Snowden, 1st Viscount Snowden, PC (/ˈsnoʊdən/; 18 July 1864 – 15 May 1937) was a British politician. A strong speaker, he became popular in trade union circles for his denunciation of capitalism as unethical and his promise of a socialist utopia.  He was the first Labour Chancellor of the Exchequer, a position he held in 1924 and again between 1929 and 1931. He broke with Labour policy in 1931, and was expelled from the party and excoriated as a turncoat, as the Party was overwhelmingly crushed that year by the National Government coalition that Snowden supported. He was succeeded as Chancellor by Neville Chamberlain.
/wiki/Consett_(UK_Parliament_constituenc: Consett was a county constituency, centred on the town of Consett in County Durham. It returned one Member of Parliament to the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom, elected by the first past the post voting system.
/wiki/Herbert_Dunnico: Rev Sir Herbert Dunnico (2 December 1875 – 2 October 1953) was a British Baptist minister, leading Freemason and Labour Party politician.
/wiki/Dewsbury_(UK_Parliament_constituen: Dewsbury is a constituency[n 1] created in 1868. This seat is represented in the House of Commons of the United Kingdom Parliament since 2019 by Mark Eastwood of the Conservative Party.[n 2]
/wiki/Benjamin_Riley: Benjamin Riley (1866 – 6 January 1946) was a British Labour Party politician.
/wiki/Dunbartonshire_(UK_Parliament_cons: Dunbartonshire was a county constituency of the House of Commons of Great Britain (at Westminster) from 1708 to 1801 and of the House of Commons of the Parliament of the United Kingdom (also Westminster) from 1801 to 1950.
/wiki/William_Henry_Porteous_Martin: William Henry Porteous Martin (15 June 1886 – 9 January 1939) was a Scottish Labour Party politician. He was Member of Parliament (MP) for Dunbartonshire from 1923 to 1924.
/wiki/East_Renfrewshire_(UK_Parliament_c: East Renfrewshire (known as Eastwood from 1983 until 2005) is a constituency of the House of Commons, to the south of Glasgow, Scotland. It elects one Member of Parliament (MP) using the first-past-the-post system of voting.
/wiki/Robert_Nichol_(Scottish_politician: Robert Nichol (12 February 1890 – 16 April 1925) was a Scottish Labour Party politician.  He was educated at Shawlands Academy, Glasgow.
